The skip link must be visible on focus (not just `:hover`) and use semantic HTML to ensure screen readers announce it. In Drupal 11, the correct `page.html.twig` pattern is:

```twig
<a href="#main-content" class="skip-link screen-reader-text">
  {{ 'Skip to main content' | t }}
</a>
```

And in your CSS (e.g., `theme-name.css`):
```css
.skip-link {
  position: absolute;
  top: -40px;
  left: 0;
  background: #000;
  color: #fff;
  padding: 8px 16px;
  z-index: 100;
  transition: top 0.2s;
}
.skip-link:focus {
  top: 0;
}

/* Screen reader only class (WCAG 2.2 compliant) */
.screen-reader-text {
  position: absolute !important;
  width: 1px !important;
  height: 1px !important;
  padding: 0 !important;
  margin: -1px !important;
  overflow: hidden !important;
  clip: rect(0, 0, 0, 0) !important;
  white-space: nowrap !important;
  border: 0 !important;
}
```

**Why this works:**
- The `screen-reader-text` class ensures visibility only to assistive technologies *until focus* (SC 1.4.10, SC 2.4.1)
- On focus, the link becomes visible (SC 2.4.7 — Focus Visibility)
- The `#main-content` target must be an `id`-matched `<main id="main-content" role="main">` (SC 1.3.1 — Info and Relationships)

**Verify with:**
```bash
npx drush cr
# Then tab to the link and confirm it jumps to main content
```

This pattern satisfies:
- SC 2.4.1 (Bypass Blocks)
- SC 2.4.7 (Focus Visibility)
- SC 1.4.10 (Reflow — no clipping of skip link on reflow)

In Drupal 11, enforce alt text by configuring the image field to make `alt` required — *not* just recommended. Here's how:

### Step 1: Make `alt` required in field settings
Navigate to:
**Structure → Content types → [Your content type] → Manage fields → [Image field]**

Under **Field settings → Alt text**:
- ✅ Check **"Required**"
- ✅ Set **"Alt text validation**" to `Default alt text` if no alt provided

### Step 2: Add client-side validation (optional but helpful)
Install the [**Image Alt Validation**](https://www.drupal.org/project/image_alt_validation) module (maintained for Drupal 10/11) to:
- Block node save if `alt` is empty or just `image123.jpg`
- Suggest alt text from file name (editor can edit before saving)

**Alternative: Use a custom form validator**
In your module's `src/EventSubscriber/ImageAltEnforcement.php`:
```php
use Drupal\Core\Form\FormStateInterface;
use Drupal\file\Entity\File;

function form_alter(&$form, FormStateInterface $form_state, $form_id) {
  if (isset($form['field_image'])) {
    $form['field_image']['#element_validate'][] = '::validateImageAlt';
  }
}

public function validateImageAlt($element, FormStateInterface $form_state) {
  $images = $form_state->getValue($element['#parents']);
  foreach ($images as $image) {
    if (empty($image['alt']) || trim($image['alt']) === '') {
      $form_state->setError($element, t('Alt text is required for accessibility (SC 1.1.1).'));
    }
  }
}
```

**Why this matters:**
- SC 1.1.1 (Non-text Content) requires all non-decorative images have meaningful alt
- Empty alt (`alt=""`) is only valid for *decorative* images — editors rarely distinguish this.
- Requiring alt text ensures meaningful alternatives are entered.

**Demo-friendly tip:** Show editors the *difference* between:
- ❌ `alt=""` on a photo of a scientist → screen reader says *nothing*
- ✅ `alt="Dr. Maya Chen analyzing soil samples in the field` → screen reader says *Dr. Maya Chen analyzing soil samples in the field`

